The '''Avenue of Stars''' was a version of the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]] in [[London]], [[England]].<ref name="usa-today04">{{cite news| url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/life/people/2004-08-23-page-walk-of-fame_x.htm|title=Page gets first star on British Walk of Fame|first=Carl|last=De Souza|newspaper=[[USA Today]]|date=23 August 2004}}</ref> It opened in 2005 with one hundred names, and was a temporary installation to accompany a TV show to celebrate ITV's 50th birthday. The Avenue of Stars was a walkway through [[Covent Garden]] passing [[St Paul's, Covent Garden|St Paul's Church]], commonly known as the "Actors' Church". It honoured individuals or groups from the entertainment industry with notable achievements. As on the [[Hollywood Walk of Fame]], the individual or group was represented by a five-pointed star containing the name set into the walkway. To qualify for a star, the individual or group had to have been from the [[United Kingdom]], the [[Republic of Ireland]], or a [[Commonwealth of Nations|Commonwealth]] nation.{{cn|date=January 2017}}
The first inductee onto the Avenue of Stars was [[Jimmy Page]], guitarist with [[Led Zeppelin]].<ref name="usa-today04"/> In 2006, all of the stars were removed, {{Why|date=January 2017}} and only the old flagstones are visible in the courtyard. American singer/songwriter Is'real Benton formed a U.S.-based eponymous foundation to restore the Walk of Fame.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.londontown.com/LondonInformation/Sights_and_Attractions/Avenue_of_the_Stars/9702|title=Avenue of the Stars Covent Garden London|publisher=londontown.com|accessdate=8 January 2017}}</ref>
